{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_mesquite_ver02/data/sn92070146/00414189441/1914012801/0670.xml":{"full_text":"2\nU. S- THEATRE\nW. R. SAWYER, Manner SAWYER GAREY, Proprietors\nSpecial, Tonight Only,\nCUSTER BAKER\nComedy Sketch Team. Entire change of pictures.\nAdmission\nIS cts\nTheatre Tulane\nC. M. Applestill, Manager\nCHANGE OF PROGRAM NIGHTLY\nBest in Singing, Best in Pictures, Best in Music\nMarie Reitz, leader Tulane Orchestra. Admission 15c\nThe El Centro National Bank\nNo 9349\nTHE BANK WITH THE EFFICIENT SERVICE.\nOFFICERS\nF. B. Fuller,\nPresident\nW. T. Bill,\nVice-President\nT. L. Doherty, Cashier\nC. G. Winter,\nAssistant Cashier\nNat.\nDIRECTORS\nW. T. Bill\nC. E. Sprouse\nI. A. Morgan\nR. W. Campbell\nIra Aten\nT. L. Doherty\nF. B. Fuller\nRESOURCES $475,000\nReceives deposits in Time Account Department from $l.OO ana\npays interest on same at 4 per cent per annum if left six months or\nlonger. _\nOur Commercial Account Department is equipped to handle your\nbusiness carefully and accurately.\nSafe Deposit Boxes for Rent.\nLeroy Holt, Pres. A. D. Leonard, Asst. Cash.\nFranklin J. Cole, V.-Pres. L- R. Wachtel, Asst. Cash.\nJ. V. Wchtel, jr., Cashier\nTHE\nFIRST NATIONAL BANK\nOF\nEl Centro,. California\nThe Lank which appreciates and protects its customers.\nHot Point Appliances For\nThe Household\nIf she didn\u2019t get one Christmas the desire of the average woman\nstill exists for an electrical device which means so much convenience\nand pleasure for her.\nAll the Hot Point Goods here.\nHOLTON POWER CO.\n\u25a0caMaMMaMMMMMmnaawH\nThere was once a man who said\n\u201cThe world is flat\u201d\u2014\nHe was related to the chap who said\n\u201cDon\u2019t use gas, it\u2019s too expensive.\u201d I\nPress* Liners for Quick Results\nIMPERIAL VALLEY PRESS, EL CENTRO., CALIFORNIA, WEDNESDAY, JANUARY 28, 1914.\nBriefs From The World\nBUSINESS IS REITER\nSAYS OGDEN ARMOUR\n(International News Night Service)\nChicago, Jan. 27. \u2014Business condi\ntions throughout the south are decid\nedly better than they were a short\ntime ago. Nineteen hundred and four\nteen promises to be a year of profita\nble activity. The present looks like a\ngood time to \u201cgo ahead.\u201d\ni That, in brief, is a summary of the\nviews expressed by a number of bank\ners. manufacturers and merchants in\nterviewed today.\nJ. Ogden Armour, who conducts one\nof the greatest business enterprises in\nthe world, expressed his satisfaction\nwith the present business outlook.\n\u201cThe business outlook is rosy in\ndeed,\" said Mr. Armour. \u201cThe manu\nfacturers will be busy and money will\nbe easy.\u201d\nBankers in Chicago repeat the opti\nmistic \u201cgo ahead\u201d assertions made ir\nhis city by Secretary of the Treasury\nMcAdoo.\n\u201cThose are my sentiments,\u201d said\nJames B. Forgan, president of the\nFirst National Bank, and added \u201cthat\nthe \u2018go ahead\u2019 spirit, coupled with s\ngeneral feeling of optimism, presaged\na better business condition.\nJohn J. Mitchell, president of tht\nIllinois Trust and Savings Bank, said; j\n\u201cBusiness sentiment has improved\ngreatly in the last week. I believe that\nif the railroad rates advances are al- j\nlowed the incident will have a splen\ndid influence based upon the better\nfeeling which already has been estab\nlished.\u201d\nManufacturers have adopted the op\ntimistic sentiments expressed by men i\nin other lines of business, according to\nJohn M. Glenn, secretary of the Illi\nnois Manufacturers\u2019 Association.\nSEEKS FORTUNE\n(International News Night Service)\nSan Francisco, Jan. 27.\u2014Investiga\ntion of the report that Anna Held, the\nactress, was made a beneficiary of the\nSacramento demimonde, divulged the\nfact that Attorney Charles F. Hanlon\nis laying a claim for Miss Held to the\nestate of Cherry de St. Maurice, the\nqueen of the Sacramento redlight dis\ntrict, who was murdered here July 8\nlast. The money involved is estimated\nat $60,000. The woman is said to have\nbeen a relative of Miss Held\u2019s father.\nRABBI UPHOLDS TANGO\nInternational News Night Service)\nSan Francisco, Jan. 27.\u2014\u201c The tangc\nis practically a reurn to the old fash\nioned dance. It is the most artistic\nand graceful of the dances,\u201d said Rabbi\nJacob Nieto ir. his sermon to Congre\ngation Sherith Israel yesterday.\nDr. Nieto preached upon the history\nof the dance from the primitive dances\nin the dawn of man\u2019s development\ndown to the modern day tango.\n\u201cSinging preceded speech, and ges\nture appeared before speech in the de\nvelopment of man,\u201d said Dr. Nieto\n\u201cDancing is in the nature of an ex\npression of admiration or worship.\n\u201cAll through the early chapters of\nthe Bible we find that dancing was an\nexpression of worship. It was the\nprimitive idea used to express oneself\n\u201cWe see this in man and in the birds.\nIt was their natural method of court\nship. There is nothing lewd or im\nproper in the dance because it is a\nspontaneous expression of nature. Tht\neffort of some people to denounce\nSan Diego\nHOTEL\nPOLHEMUS\n7th and C Streets\nNew fireproof Class A building. 100\nelegantly furnished room.;. Room\nwith bath SI.OO. Others with bath\nprivilege for less. A special feature,\na dainty breakfast will be served to\nall guests FREE each morning, in\norder to introduce this new home-like\nhotel. No other hotel offers such a\ntreat.\nBeans! Yes, Ordinary Pink Frijoles\nThe sort with which you are all familiar. The one ho often re* 1\nK\u00bbrded lightly\u2014-and partaken of heavily\u2014and the same old bean\nwe mi olten laugh over. If we knew more of its food-bearing qual- l\nilies we would \u201ctake off our hat*\u201d to the bean.\nW e are offering a regular 23c size of the canned pork and beans j\nat 13c and the smaller size at three for 25c.\nHotter get a case at these prices. There\u2019s more food hound up\nin the same amount of skin than 10 times the amount of beef\u2014and j\ncompare the cost.\nROSS SfUARTS GROCERY i\nu Thc Store With a Conscience\u201d I\ndancing has only aroused resentment\nand bravado.\n\u201cThe tango is practically a return\nto the old fashioned type of dance. 1\ncan see nothing objectionable about it.\nIt is akin to the Sraband and other\nsimilar dances where there is not\nco much contact as in the waltz and\ntwo-step.\n\u201cThe most artistic and graceful of\nthe modern dances is the tango, be\ncause it is a combination of the old\nand beautiful Spanish dances and the\nwaltz.\u201d\nMORAN QUITS FIGHT\n(International News Night Service)\nNew Y'ork, Jan. 27. \u2014Young Shu\ngrue had Owen Moran practically out\nin the seventh round here tonight\nMoran refused to continue.\nJohnny Dundee outpointed Sapper\nO\u2019Neill, English lightweight, in a six\nround bout.\nBattling Levisky won on points\nfrom Soldier Kerns.\nFOR AMBASSADORS\nInternational News Night Service)\nWashington, Jan. 27. \u2014It is learned\n\u2018hat Thomas Nelson Fage will be ap\npointed ambassador to France, and\nhat William McCombs, chairman of\nthe Democratic national committee\n,vil be ambassador to Italy\nYANDERBILS RESCUED\n(International News Night Service)\nNew Orleans, Jan. 27. \u2014A wireless\nmessage tonight states that Mr. and\nMrs. Frederick W. Vanderbilt and\nparty have been rescued from the\nacht Warnier, which was wrecked off\n\nthe Colombian coast. The party was\ntransferred to the United fruit steam\ner Almirante.\nGOETHALS APPOINTED\nInternational News Night Service)\nWashington, Jan. 27.\u2014President\nWilson today entered the tug of war\nbetween Mayor Mitchell and himself\nby sending Colonel Goethals a tele\ngram naming him first governor of\nthe Panama Canal zone. The order\nmakes the new government effective\nApril 1.\nLAND BLUE JACKETS\n(International News Night Service)\nPort Au Price, Jan. 27.\u201481ue jack\nets from the battleship Montana\nwere landed here late today when\nfighting between the revolutionists\nand government troops broke out.\nGerman troops were also landed from\nthe cruiser Vineta.\nWANTS JOB BACK\n(International News Night Service)\nSan Francisco, Jan. 27.\u2014Former\nNaval Constructor Holden A. Evans,\nwho was transferred from Mare Island\nin 1910 after his sensational divorce\nsuit, in which he accused a brother of\nficer, \u201cBoy\u201d Osburn, of kissing his\nwife, is making efforts to obtain rein\nstatement, according to reports re\nceived at the navy yard yesterday. His\nfriends there say he is on excellent\nterms with the present administrate/\nand hopes to be put back in his old po\nsition at Marc Island and to realize\nhis ambition of becoming director of\nnavy yards.\nACCIDENT, CORONER\u2019S VERDICT\n(International News Night Service)\nNew York, Jan. 27.\u2014\u201c Unavoidable\naccident\u201d was the verdict returned to\nday by the coroner\u2019s jury in the case\nof Richard Lankford, vice president\niof the Southern Railway, whose body\nwas found Friday in his apartment. He\nhad been asphyxiated. The coroner had\nordered the body returned to the\napartments when an attempt was\nmade to move it, stating he had in\nformation rendering further investiga\ntion advisable. After the inquest the\nbody was released.\nPOPE REMOVES BAN\n(International News Night Service)\nPaiis, Jan. 27.\u2014According to re\nports reaching here from Rome, the\npope has removed the ban instituted\nagainst the tango, with the provision\nthat the name of the dance be changed.\nRUSSELL FIGHTS CASE\n(International News Night Service)\nSacramento, Jan. 27.\u2014A fight\nagainst the extradition of Warren B.\nRussell, now held in the San Francisco\ncity jail, wanted in Tazewell county,\n111., on the charge of wife abandon\nment, will be made by Attorney John\nS. Hogan of San Francisco before\nGovernor Johnson today.\nAttorney Hogan will resist the ex\ntradition on the ground that the of\nfense charged is not an indictable of\nj fense, nor a felony in Illinois, and that\nthe extradition should therefore not\nbe granted.\nWarren B. Russell is the son of Mrs.\nAlice Russell of Chicago, who is the\nowner of a large farm property near\nSaginaw. Cash bail is ready at any\ntime Russell is temporarily released.\nVALUABLE HORSE\n(International News Night Service)\nPalm Beach, Fla., Jan. 27.\u20141 n a let\nter to a friend here from Richard Cro\nker in Dublin, Ireland, Mr. Croker en\nclosed a copy of a Dublin paper re\nporting the largest offer ever made for\nhis famous sire Orby, but mentioning\nno figure. The owner of the letter\nsays the offer was greater than $200,-\n000, but says no amount of money will\nbuy the horse.\n(International News Nijit Serv'ce)\nWashington, Jan. 27.\u2014Threats of\nhis life were sent to Senator Kenyon,\nauthor of the red light bill, which\nwiped out Washington\u2019s famous red\nlight district. The letters were post\nmarked Washington and it is believed\nthey have come from members of the\nsegregated quarter. Surrounding\ntowns and cities have entered a protest\nagainst their threatened inva\u00bb\u00bbon by\nWashington dive keepelfc.\nTO VISIT ARGENTINA\n(International News Night Service)\nMadrid, Jan. 27.\u2014A newspaper here\nquotes Premier Dato as saying that\nKing Alfonso will go to Argentina in\nJune to make the acquaintance of a\ncountry whither so many Spaniards\nhave emigrated who remain profound\nly attached to the mother country.\u201d\nThe king will be accompanied by\nthe premier and the minister of mar\nine. He will sail on a modern Spanish\nliner and will be escorted by warships.\nHe is expected to be absent two\nmonths.\nPremier Dato thinks the visit will\nbe useful in promoting commercial re\nlations between Spain and Argentina.\n(International News Nighi Service)\nSacramento, Jan. 27.\u2014John M. Esh\nleman today announced himself a can\ndidate for lieutenant governor on the\nticket with Johnson. The governor\ntonight said:\n\u201cTo no one man do the people owe\nmore than to John M. Eshleman. With\nfairness, impartiality and remarkable\nability he has presided over the rail\nroad commission. He today has rec\nognized the authority of the United\nStates upon public utilities and their\nregulations.\n\u201cSuch men are at once the product\nand pride of Progressiveism. His eletv\ntion is a matter of course.\u201d\nFOR A DRY OAKLAND\n(International News Night Service)\nSan Francisco, Jan. 27. \u2014\u201cClosing of\nthe saloons in Oakland,\u201d said D. M.\nGandier of the anti-saloon league in\nthe meeting of protest against the\nHart ordinance held yesterday after\nnoon, \u201cso far from hurting business\nwill actually increase it and increase\nrents. It is true that rents of some par\nticular little shack may fall, but rents\nas a whole will rise and thus make up\nfor any loss.\u201d\nThe speaker then cited concrete ex\namples in Los Angeles and other Cal\nifornia cities.\nCONTRACTS FOR TOBACCO\n(International News Night Service)\nDinuba, Jan. 27.\u2014A New York\nbuyerhas closed with the Turkish to\nbacco growers of this district con\ntracts for the delivery of 100,000\npounds of the 1914 crop, at an average\nprice of <53 cents. It is said that this\nbuyer is negotiating contracts for the\nentire 1914 output of Tulare and of\nFresno counties.\nPATTERSON ARRIVES\n(International News Night Service)\nNew York, Jan. 27. \u2014The Rev. Rob\nert J. Patterson, originator of the\n\u201ccatch my pal\u201d temperance movement;\narrived from Queenstown by the White\nStar liner Cedric, taking a berth in\nthe second cabin because there were\nmany more voyagers there in influence\nwith exhortations and buttons.\nBRADLEY MARTIN HONORED\n(International News Night Service)\nEdinburgh, Jan. 27.\u2014The tradesmen\nresidents of Inverness, in the Scot 1\ntish Highlands, are subscribers to a\nmemorial to the late Bradley Marti)\nin recognition of the generosity and\ninterest the New Yorker took in their\nwelfare.\n\u201cThe proposed memorial will be a\nbronze bust on a marble pedestal\nwhich will be unveiled in Glen Ur\nquhart, near Ralrnacaan, where the fa\nmous Bradley Martin shooting parties\nhave taken place for dO years.\nMain Street,\n120 feet at a snap. Gage Wach\ntel, <>l4 Main street.\u2014Adv.\nJOIN THE RUSH TO INVEST AROUND IMPERIAL JUNCTION,\nWHERE THE $2,000,000 SYNDICATE WILL SOON TRANSFORM\nTHEIR 47.000 ACRES INTO VERDANT FIELDS OF ALFALFA,\nCOTTON AND FRUIT.\nX,\n\n$2,000,000\nSYNDICATE.\nSECTION\nR.R.LAND.\nO\nSECTION\n'V\n\nSECTIO\n'S'\n5\n\nSECTION\nPer Lot.\n>.000,000\n.SYNDICATE\nAll Lota\nare\nOne Price\nand\nOne Size,\n50x150\nFeet.\nNo Small\nLots.\n9\n$2,000,000\nSYNDICATE\n$4 Cash,\n$4 Per Month.\nTO\nEL CENTRO\nNo Interest\nNo Taxes\nLIKE A DIAMOND\nLISTEN!\nSurrounded by the lands of the\n\u201952,000,000 Syndicate who will\" soon\ntransform the same into fields of alfalfa, cotton and fruit. Grasp\nthis grand opportunity.\nBuy in the midst of where future\ngreat improvements will soon occur.\nPrice will soon be raised. Don\u2019t delay. Buy now. 25 per cent\nguaranteed increase in one year, as per written contract. The grand\nfuture of the region around Imperial Junction is as certain as the sun\nwill rise tomorrow. Railroad map show's 200 acres reserved for switch\ning yards. Means business. Get in now'. Title of Tract No. 1 of Im\nperial county perfect, being United States Patent No. 87384. Map\nduly approved by Board of Supervisors and on file in County Re\ncorder\u2019s office of Imperial County, Page 15 of Book 1 of Maps. All\nlots are one price, $9O per lot, $4 cash, $4 per month, no interest and\nno taxes. First come, first served. Full information, map and Illus\ntrated Prospectus will be sent you absolutely free upon application.\nNo trouble to answer questions. Don\u2019t send money, simply write.\nHarbor City Investment Co.\n604 Main Street, Security Bank Building, El Centro, California.\nCUT THIS OUT AND MAIL.\nHARBOR CITY INVESTMENT CO.,\n604 Main St., Security Bank Bldg., El Centro, California.\nPlease send me full information, Map and Illustrated Prospectus\nof Tract No. 1 of Imperial County, without any obligation to pur\nchase and without any expense to me for reply. I think I can buy\nlots at $9O per lot, $4 cash and $4 per month, no in\nterest and no taxes.\nNAME\nSTREET.\nKindly state how many lots desired.\nMT-1-28\nTHE BANK THAT MADE BROADWAY\n\nInterest Paid\nOn Time\nDeposit!\nu\nK\n-n\nv\\\nIndependent\nProgressive\nDependable\nBroadway at Second\nLOUIS J. WILDE, President. S. A. REED, Cashier\nWhen In San Diego Make This Bank Your Headquarters\n\u201cSUNSET\nLIMITED\nMardi Gras Celebration\nNew Orleans, Feb. i\u2018J-24\nEVERY DAY\n(NO EXTRA FARE)\nEASTBOUND\nLeave El Centro 8:25 a. m.\nArrive New Orleans 8:50 p. in.\nTWO NIGHTS TO NEW ORLEANS\nFOUR NIGHTS TO NEW YORK\nEquipment (All steel)\n1\u2014 6-compartment drawing room ob\nservation car.\n2 12-Section drawing room cars.\nI\u2014Tourist sleeping car through to\nWashington, I). C.\nI\u2014Dining car.\nI\u2014Baggage car.\nEvery convenience.\nService unexcelled.\nOil burning locomotives.\nRoadbed rock ballasted and oiled.\nProtected by block signals.\nConnections made at New Orleans\nwith fast limited trains for all East\nern points.\nAlso with Southern Pacific steamships\nfor New York.\nTickets the same as all rail and in\nclude berth and meals on ship.\nSOUTHERN PACIFIC SERVICE IS\nTHE STANDARD\nSOUTHERN PACIFIC\nThe Exposition Line 1915\nS. F. WILLARD, Agent, El Centro\nThe L. W. Blinn Lumber Company\nIncorporated\nWholesale and retail dealers in Puget Sound Pine and Redwood 1 umber,\nRailroad Ties, Telegraph Poles, Shingles, Doors, Sash and General Build\ning Material. Agents for Johns-Manvill Asbestos Roofing.\nThird and Main streets. L. 11. SCOTT, Agent Telephone Main 5","height":"29468","width":"23376"}}
